<div id="stitle" style="display:none;">Notebook Entry</div>
<dl id="n38134b"> <dt class="nbunit"><a name="n38" href="#n38134b">N38 (VI.B.32)</a>:  <a href="../../ff/fnbs/n38all.htm#n38134b"> 134(b)</a></dt> <dd> <blockquote> sponging house</blockquote> <dd class="well"> <blockquote class="sources">Michael Arne (1741-86) <font color="green">[&hellip;]</font> was the composer of many songs, and pieces for the harpsichord, on which instrument he was a skilled executant. The younger Arne died in great destitution, for he was of a dreamy, shiftless nature. Kelly stated that &ldquo;Arne, not content with being one of the greatest musical geniuses the world ever produced, wished also to possess the philosopher&apos;s stone; and, fancying himself a great alchemist, actually took a house at Richmond, near Dublin, and, neglecting all his pupils, gave himself up to a scientific search for gold. The consequences were ruin and a <mark>spunging-house</mark>. <font color="green">[&hellip;]</font>&rdquo; <small> S.M. Ellis, <a name="ELMK" href="../../ff/fdra/fdex.htm#ELMK"><cite title="source">The Life of Michael Kelly</cite></a>,(1930) 22n1</small></blockquote> </dd></dl>
